# Fluff Date: 2026-02-28 17:47:08
overview:<p>The Kiso is a hundred-ton quad IndustrialMech introduced in 2638 by Osaka Heavy Metrics for the Draconis Combine. Designed during the Star League's golden age, the Kiso was conceived as a mobile command platform for the massive construction operations then reshaping worlds across the Combine. Unlike typical IndustrialMechs that served a single function, the Kiso was intended to allow a construction supervisor to both operate heavy equipment and simultaneously coordinate entire building projects from the cockpit. Its four-legged configuration provided exceptional stability on rough construction sites, and the design quickly became a fixture on major infrastructure projects throughout Combine space.</p><p>Though the Succession Wars brought centuries of lost production, the Kiso's unmatched combination of heavy construction capability and integrated project management systems ensured it remained a prized asset wherever surviving examples could be found. The resumption of manufacturing in the late thirty-first century restored the Kiso to its former prominence across Combine construction sites.</p>

capabilities:<p>The Kiso mounts a tungsten-cored Osaka heavy-duty pile driver in the right torso, a formidable tool capable of driving foundation pilings and demolishing reinforced structures with equal ease. A Nagy diamond-studded rock cutter on the left torso handles quarry work, demolition of ferrocrete, and general embankment operations. Two telescoping HM-1 lift hoists, one per side torso, provide crane capability for medium-scale lifting operations. Twenty tons of modular cargo container space in the center torso allows the Kiso to carry tools, equipment, and supplies directly to the work site, with removable containers enabling rapid load swaps.</p><p>The Kiso's true distinction lies in its command and control capabilities. The HeadMaster 41-con communications suite, upgraded to a civilian command version in 2703, provides network uplinks to planetary databases, weather satellites, security cameras, and utility grids. A mini-holographic projector displays layered blueprints from any angle, giving the operator virtual control over complex construction projects. The Diplan I-TT tracking system supports equipment coordination across the work site.</p><p>Powered by a Nissan 200 fusion engine, the Kiso achieves a modest top speed of thirty-two kilometers per hour, adequate for transit between job sites. Tybalt Blue Heavy Industrial Plate armor protects against workplace hazards such as falling debris and rock fragments, though it offers minimal resistance against dedicated military weapons. The quad chassis design trades manipulative flexibility for the exceptional stability required when operating heavy construction equipment at elevation or on uneven terrain.</p>

deployment:<p>The K-3N-KR4 is the standard production model of the Kiso, representing the 2703 upgrade from the original KR3 design. The primary improvement was the installation of a civilian-grade command console, transforming the foreman's position into a comprehensive project management station with access to planetary networks, permit systems, and holographic blueprint displays. This version carries the full complement of construction tools including the Osaka pile driver, Nagy rock cutter, twin lift hoists, and twenty tons of modular cargo capacity. Four Osaka Heavy Metrics plants across the Draconis Combine produce the KR4 at Dieron, New Samarkand, Philadelphia, and Togura, with production having resumed after the 3050s following centuries of technological loss.</p>

history:<p>The Kiso's origins trace to 2638, when Osaka Heavy Metrics introduced the massive quad IndustrialMech to serve as the centerpiece of the Draconis Combine's ambitious construction programs. During the Star League era, Kisos were deployed to major building projects across Combine space, where they became familiar sights on construction sites lasting years at a time. Their operators developed a tradition of decorating the machines in vivid colors and street art, with each new project adding to the overall design in a manner reminiscent of yakuza tattoos. The original KR3 model received its major upgrade to the KR4 standard in 2703, adding the civilian command console that became the design's defining feature.</p><p>The First Succession War proved catastrophic for Kiso production. All three of Osaka Heavy Metrics' main manufacturing plants were destroyed, and the sophisticated communications suites and command consoles that defined the design could not be replicated with the degrading technology base of the Succession Wars era. The surviving Kisos became exceedingly rare, their numbers dwindling over the centuries as attrition claimed machines that could not be properly maintained or replaced. By the early thirty-first century, functional Kisos were precious assets, jealously guarded by their owners.</p><p>The technological renaissance sparked by the rediscovery of the Helm Memory Core eventually reached Osaka Heavy Metrics, which recovered the technical specifications needed to manufacture the Kiso's advanced systems. By the 3050s the company had reacquired the capability to produce the communications and command equipment, and production resumed across four assembly lines at Dieron, Togura, New Samarkand, and Philadelphia. Osaka Heavy Metrics timed the full restart to coincide with the company's five-hundredth anniversary in 3070, a milestone that also coincided with surging demand for heavy construction equipment as the Word of Blake's campaigns drove massive rebuilding efforts across the Inner Sphere.</p><p>The Jihad disrupted production at Dieron, which fell under Word of Blake occupation, though the remaining three Combine-held facilities continued manufacturing. Osaka Heavy Metrics also leveraged its industrial expertise during the Jihad to support military production for the desperate Draconis Combine Mustered Soldiery, developing military designs alongside its civilian product lines. Following the Jihad, Dieron passed through Republic of the Sphere control before eventually returning to Combine hands, while the other three facilities maintained uninterrupted Combine ownership throughout the conflict and its aftermath.</p>

